yment as a problem of individual employability. Drawing on untapped government records, it sheds much-needed light on internal bureaucratic struggles over the direction of labour market policy in Canada and makes a key contribution to Canadian political science, economics, public administration, and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aactivation.  agovernmentality.  ajobs public employment services.  alabour market.  amanagerialism.  amanpower.  apolitical economy.  astreet-level bureaucracy.  aunemployment.  awelfare-to-work.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753024240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487530242.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles